Hi Lino

the delivery tracker exists on Asana. you have access
https://app.asana.com/1/884979004051272/project/1211430291388699/list/1211433360140555

what we have covered already in the SOPs is "Fulfillment". inside of
"Fulfillment" there is Maintenance. this is keeping the Clio matter up to
date

in addition to but in parallel to Fulfillment is Delivery. i will send you
a breakdown  / scope statement of what should Fulfillment Maintenance and
what should be delivery. delivery is the more time sensitive stuff




*Matthew AJ* *Levine*

Barrister & Solicitor


This message may contain confidential and / or privileged information and
is only to be used by the intended recipient. If you received this message
in error, please delete it and notify us. Thank you.




On Fri, Feb 20, 2026 at 9:08 AM Lino Bernal <ops@levinelegal.ca> wrote:

> Hi Matthew,
>
>    1. *On the Delivery System,* I’m comfortable finishing the setup on my
>    end. Since a task can exist in multiple boards in Asana, updating it in one
>    place updates it everywhere. So there’s no real risk of duplication as long
>    as we’re multi-homing the same task
>    2. *On training the Exec Admin: *Onboarding and Opening are about 90%
>    documented. We just need to finalize some of the details. Where things
>    become more dynamic is Maintenance since its ongoing administration and
>    client support. That means new, matter-specific tasks that can’t always be
>    templated. If helpful, you can forward client emails directly to me. I can
>    then create and assign subtasks under the appropriate Matter in Asana. I’ve
>    sent how to provide access to your email, please let me know if you would
>    like me to resend
>    3. *On delegating billable / fee earner work: *If you forward client
>    requests to me, I can assign and manage those tasks. That would include
>    backend tracking such as: Time expectations, Required materials, Task
>    breakdown, Follow-ups etc. We can refine that structure as we go and making
>    sure the board is ready for them
>
> I think the next steps right now are the following:
>
>    1. Review the Onboarding SOP
>    <https://docs.google.com/document/d/1cVd1soOFDJab31AtXQGpkmrieMRJ2aAHyHJoNwUNO9U/edit?tab=t.g9sw0lwzeh6i#bookmark=id.fm2lawjokry5>
>    and Opening SOP
>    <https://docs.google.com/document/d/1cVd1soOFDJab31AtXQGpkmrieMRJ2aAHyHJoNwUNO9U/edit?tab=t.g9sw0lwzeh6i#bookmark=id.fm2lawjokry5>
>
>    2. Establish the Maintenance flow (this can be as simple as forwarding
>    emails to me so I can assign and manage tasks, since requirements will vary
>    by client. I just want clarity on how this should function in practice.)
>    3. Sending the Delivery Tracker
>    4. Reconcile the matters in Clio and ensure all Delivery–Essential,
>    Delivery–Strategic, and Delivery–Standard matters have a corresponding card
>
> Thanks!
>
> On Mon, Feb 16, 2026 at 6:02 AM Matthew Levine <matthew@levinelegal.ca>
> wrote:
>
>> Hey Lino
>>
>> let me send you a counter-proposal :) we can cancel this weeks 1:1
>>
>> in the meantime, can I just confirm our high level architecture
>>
>> Services Department, which includes
>>
>>    - Fulfillment System (Your operations work is Active, and you are
>>    also filling in by implementing the exec assist work)

>>          - 2) i am starting to delegate billable / fee earner work to

emails.snippet: Shalom, Purim is a joyful time of the year and a really fun time at the Village Shul. We hope to see you over Purim and joining us in the Mitzvos of the Day. Charity: There is a tradition before the
emails.body:
Shalom,

Purim is a joyful time of the year and a really fun time at the Village Shul. We hope to see you over Purim and joining us in the Mitzvos of the Day. 🎉

Charity: 💰
There is a tradition before the Megillah Reading on the first night to give Machtzis Hashekel (3 half dollars or $1.50) to Charity to commemorate our responsibility to the community as was done in the times of the Bait Hamikdash.

There is also a Mitzvah to give Matonos L’evyonim (a cash gift to the poor) on Purim. The Rabbi’s can distribute your gift to those in need by an online donation  HERE   today, or with cash at the Megillah Reading.

Megillah: 📜
On Monday, March 2nd at 6:20 PM, please join us for an introduction to Purim, followed by the Wendy Zinner z”l Legacy of Leadership Award – “Eshet Chayil.”

The Megillah Readings will take place at:
• 6:45 PM – First Reading
• 8:30 PM – Second Reading

Following the first Megillah Reading, refreshments will be served for breaking the fast. All are invited to attend.
Come in your costume and claim your treat! 🎭

On Tuesday, March 3rd, Megillah Readings will take place at 7:25 AM and 4:15 PM.
Please see the full schedule below for all reading times.

Mishloach Manot: 🎁
The Shul initiative of Mishloach Manot is well on the way. Thank you to those who participated.

You can distribute your own as well by packing 2 food items and giving them to a Jewish friend or neighbor.

Purim Party: 🍽️The Purim Carnival will start at 3:00 PM on March 3rd.
To register, Please click  HERE .The Shul Purim in the Caribbean Party will begin at 5:00 PM on Tuesday, March 3rd (sold out event).
Looking forward to spending this fun days together,
Rabbi Tzvi Sytner
Rabbi Shlomo Katz          CLICK HERE TO REGISTER         CLICK HERE TO DONATE             www.ourvillageshul.com      The Village Shul
1072 Eglinton Avenue West
Toronto, ON M6C 2E2
https://www.ourvillageshul.com  
Unsubscribe | Manage Preferences
Delivered to matthew@levinelegal.caCan't see any pictures?

emails.snippet: Trouble viewing this email? Read it online (Le texte français se trouve sous le texte anglais) Please join us for the annual International Women's Day program - an engaging, inclusive, and action-
emails.body:
(Le texte français se trouve sous le texte anglais)
Please join us for the annual International Women’s Day program - an engaging, inclusive, and action-focused conversation dedicated to raising awareness, driving meaningful change, and inspiring collective action toward a more equitable justice system and society for all women.
Thursday, March 5, 2026
5:45 - 7:45 p.m. 
Virtual program
This year’s program will feature a dynamic discussion on advancing gender equality through law, policy, and collective advocacy, while recognizing the persistent barriers and discrimination women continue to face within legal systems and society at large.
Guest speakers will explore critical issues at the intersection of women’s rights and justice, including:
·Safeguarding the freedom to participate fully and lead in all areas of society
·Addressing systemic shortcomings that fail survivors
·Confronting bias embedded in institutions and processes
·Examining the disproportionate impact of these shortcomings on marginalized women
·Identifying practical ways to advance substantive equality
Drawing on urgent, real-world challenges, this program will also include a timely examination of the unique pressures confronting women in the legal professions, with particular attention to the safety and security of Indigenous and racialized women. We invite all participants to reflect, engage, and take action in advancing a more just and equitable society.
This program has been accredited for 2 hours of EDI Professionalism content.
This program is being organized by the Law Society of Ontario, Ontario Bar Association (OBA) and the OBA Women Lawyers Forum, Women’s Law Association of Ontario (WLAO), Women’s Legal Education and Action Fund (LEAF), Barbra Schlifer Commemorative Clinic, Young Women in Law (YWL) and Women in Canadian Criminal Defence (WiCCD).  
RSVP
This public event is free. For additional information and to register to receive the webcast link, please RSVP (https://trk.cp20.com/click/ci9l-30eu9v-4imgv8-kwske330/). 
The Law Society of Ontario makes reasonable accommodations to enable persons with disabilities to attend and participate in its programs, including providing auxiliary aids and services upon request and removing architectural and communication barriers that are structural in nature where readily achievable. To request any auxiliary aids or services or if you have any questions regarding accessibility, please contact equityevents@lso.ca (mailto:equityevents@lso.ca). 
The Law Society of Ontario regularly livestreams LSO events and takes photographs, audio, and video recordings, and creates other forms of content during its events. Please review the Notice of multimedia and disclaimer (https://trk.cp20.com/click/ci9l-30eu9v-4imgv9-kwske331/) for more information. 

(Le texte français se trouve sous le texte anglais)
Veuillez-vous joindre à nous pour le programme annuel de la Journée internationale des femmes - une conversation engageante, inclusive et axée sur l’action dédiée à sensibiliser, à provoquer un changement significatif et à inspirer une action collective vers un système de justice plus équitable et une société pour toutes les femmes. 
Jeudi 5 mars 2026
De 17 h 45 à 19 h 45 
Programme virtuel
Le programme de cette année comprendra une discussion dynamique sur la promotion de l’égalité des sexes par la loi, les politiques et le plaidoyer collectif, tout en reconnaissant les obstacles persistants et la discrimination auxquels les femmes continuent de faire face dans les systèmes juridiques et dans la société en général. Les conférencières invitées exploreront des questions critiques à l’intersection des droits des femmes et de la justice - allant de la sauvegarde de la liberté de participer pleinement et se diriger dans tous les domaines de la société, à la résolution des lacunes systémiques qui laissent tomber les survivantes, renforce les préjugés, et ont un impact disproportionné sur les femmes marginalisées. La conversation mettra également en évidence des moyens concrets de renouveler et de renforcer notre engagement commun à atteindre l’égalité réelle. 
S’appuyant sur des défis urgents et concrets, ce programme comprendra également un examen opportun des pressions uniques auxquelles sont confrontées les femmes dans la profession juridique, en accordant une attention particulière à la sécurité des femmes autochtones et racialisées. Nous invitons tous les participants à réfléchir, à s’engager et à agir pour faire progresser une société plus juste et équitable. 
Ce programme a été agréé pour 2 heures de professionnalisme en EDI.
Ce programme a été organisé par le Barreau de l’Ontario, l’Association du Barreau de l’Ontario (ABO), le forum des avocates de l’ABO, la Women’s Law Association of Ontario (WLAO), le Fonds d’action et d’éducation juridique pour les femmes (FAEJ), la clinique commémorative Barbra Schlifer, la Young Women in Law (YWL) et la Women in Canadian Criminal Defence (WiCCD). 
RSVP
Cet évènement public est gratuit. Pour obtenir d’autres renseignements et recevoir le lien à la webémission, veuillez répondre ici. (https://trk.cp20.com/click/ci9l-30eu9v-4imgva-kwske331/)
Le Barreau de l’Ontario prend des mesures d’adaptation raisonnables pour permettre aux personnes handicapées de participer à des programmes, notamment en fournissant des aides et des services auxiliaires sur demande et en éliminant les obstacles architecturaux et de communication qui sont de nature structurelle lorsque cela est facilement réalisable. Pour demander de l’aide ou un service auxiliaire ou si vous avez des questions concernant l’accessibilité, veuillez contacter equityevents@lso.ca (mailto:equityevents@lso.ca). 
Le Barreau de l’Ontario diffuse régulièrement des évènements en direct et prend des photos, des enregistrements audio et vidéo, et crée d’autres formes de contenu pendant ses évènements. Veuillez consulter l’Avis de multimédia et de non-responsabilité (https://trk.cp20.com/click/ci9l-30eu9v-4imgvb-kwske332/) pour en savoir plus.
https://www.facebook.com/LawSocietyLSO (https://trk.cp20.com/click/ci9l-30eu9v-4imgvc-kwske333/)https://twitter.com/LawsocietyLSO (https://trk.cp20.com/click/ci9l-30eu9v-4imgvd-kwske334/)https://www.linkedin.com/company/53434 (https://trk.cp20.com/click/ci9l-30eu9v-4imgve-kwske335/)

Toronto, ON M5H 2N6

Your new command center for agentic coding*
The Codex app is designed for multi-tasking with agents ( https://openai.com/index/introducing-the-codex-app/ ) and connects to all your tools. Supervise parallel workstreams, review changes cleanly, and stay in control from background execution to shipped code. And for a limited time, try Codex ( https://openai.com/codex/ ) in ChatGPT Free and ChatGPT Go.

*Make Codex smarter everywhere
* GPT-5.3-Codex can make Codex a more autonomous coworker ( https://openai.com/index/introducing-gpt-5-3-codex/ ) across all Codex surfaces: the app, CLI, IDE extensions, and web—and is now available in the Responses API, too. We also released a research preview of GPT-5.3-Codex-Spark, a smaller, faster model built for real-time coding. ( https://openai.com/index/introducing-gpt-5-3-codex-spark/ )

*Speed up tool-heavy agent runs with WebSockets
* WebSockets in the Responses API speed up agent runs by 20–40% ( https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/websocket-mode ) by maintaining a persistent connection—so you only send new inputs instead of full context each turn.

*Build longer-running agents with the API
* We’ve added an OpenAI-hosted container (with networking), Skills, and automatic compaction to the Responses API. This enables long-running workflows ( https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/tools-shell ) on computers that execute tasks more reliably ( https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/tools-skills ) and work across millions of tokens ( https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/compaction ).

*Upgrade your Realtime voice stack*
If you’re building voice agents, gpt-realtime-1.5 is the new default ( https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/realtime/ ) stronger multilingual conversation, tighter instruction following, and more reliable tool calling.

*Generate images in bulk with the Batch API
* You can now use the Batch API with our gpt-image models to send async groups of requests at 50% lower cost ( https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/batch ) , with access to a separate pool of higher rate limits. This is available for our gpt-image models ( https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/image-generation ) : gpt-image-1.5, chatgpt-image-latest, gpt-image-1, and gpt-image-1-mini.

🧰 Build kit

Guides, blogs, and things worth cloning

*Automate the repetitive stuff:* Andrew from the Codex engineering team shows how he uses Codex Automations to offload recurring tasks ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xHnlzAPD9QI ) —what to automate, how to set it up, and where it saves real time.

*Work on two things at once (without chaos):* Joey from the Codex engineering team demos parallel development with Codex worktrees: delegate a feature in one worktree, keep coding in another, then review and land both PRs. Parallel workflows turn waiting time into progress. ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9ohXlkbXiM4 )

*Build agents that can run for hours:* Shell tool, Skills, and automatic Compaction are the core primitives for long-running agents. Get our tips for practical patterns ( https://developers.openai.com/blog/skills-shell-tips ) to execute commands, reuse behaviors, and keep context stable over time.

*Build agents that behave (and remember):* Two Cookbook articles break down how prompt structure shapes agent behavior and reliability ( https://cookbook.openai.com/examples/gpt-5/prompt_personalities ) and how context engineering determines what gets retained vs. dropped ( https://cookbook.openai.com/examples/agents_sdk/context_personalization ).

*Did your agent improve... or just change?:* Evals turn “feels better” into actual checks. ( https://developers.openai.com/blog/eval-skills ) Did the skill trigger, do the right thing, and leave things clean? This will help you catch regressions early.

*Stop recomputing the same prompts:* Prompt caching reuses shared prefixes ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tECAkJAI_Vk ) to make AI apps faster and cheaper at scale.

🛠️ Devs in the wild

From side projects to professional work

*Company spotlight: Skyscanner*

By wiring the Codex CLI into JetBrains ( https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1XkVsE9-ZK4 ) IDEs via the Model Context Protocol (MCP), Skyscanner gave Codex access to real IDE context ( https://developers.openai.com/blog/skyscanner-codex-jetbrains-mcp ). This unlocks smarter problem-solving, faster feedback loops, and measurable gains in development speed.

*Developer spotlight: Agrim Singh*

Check out the full thread on X from Agrim ( https://x.com/agrimsingh/status/2022028612770443385 ) , CTO of Niyam AI (and Codex ambassador!) for an early wl1 demo, the repo, and notes on the build.

📣 Insider scoop

Go behind the scenes with OpenAI engineers

*Harness engineering ( https://openai.com/index/harness-engineering/ ) : leveraging Codex in an agent-first world*

Note from the author: “Our team has varied experience, and humans can’t fully mind-meld. Codex can: when we encode ‘what good looks like’ in the repo, every run applies it consistently—and the gains compound.”

- Ryan Lopopolo, Member of Technical Staff at OpenAI. Keep up with his work on X ( https://x.com/_lopopolo ).

*Inside the Postgres Setup ( https://openai.com/index/scaling-postgresql/ ) Powering 800M ChatGPT Users*

Note from the author: “Before OpenAI, I learned the hard way that startups often over-engineer. Here, I’ve been impressed by how far a deliberately simple setup—a single PostgreSQL writer—can scale with the right optimizations and discipline. That inspired me to share what I’ve seen.”

- Bohan Zhang, Member of Technical Staff at OpenAI. K eep up with his work on X ( https://x.com/BohanZhangOT ).

*What Actually Happens Inside an AI Coding Agent ( https://openai.com/index/unrolling-the-codex-agent-loop/ ) (We Unrolled It)*

Note from the author: “Despite being on Codex CLI since the beginning, I learned a lot from putting this post together, so hopefully you will, too!”

- Michael Bolin, Member of Technical Staff at OpenAI. Follow more of his journey on Threads ( https://www.threads.com/@bolinfest/post/DT3cVLlkubK ).

Happy building and vibing,

The OpenAI Team

1455 3rd Street
San Francisco CA 94158

emails.body:
Hi Matthew,

I have included my comments below in red.

Let me know what you think. I will prepare the updated ISC and send that
over to you.

Also, in terms of timing i have spent about 4 hours on all of the
preparation of corporate records, reviewing of all of the documents and
updating of the documents. I just wanted to keep you apprised for timing as
we discussed previously.

Let me know if you have any questions or if there is anything further you
need from me.

Best,

*Laura Hinton*

Barrister & Solicitor
1235 Bay Street, Suite 700, TORONTO, M5R 3K4

T: +1 (647) 598-2598


This message may contain confidential and/or privileged information and is
only to be used by the intended recipient. If you received this message in
error, please delete it and notify us. Thank you.


---------- Forwarded message ---------
From: Matthew Levine <matthew@levinelegal.ca>
Date: Wed, Feb 25, 2026 at 1:20 PM
Subject: Re: Corporate Records for Legacy Global Group Inc.
To: Laura Hinton <laura@levine-law.ca>


Hi Laura

Let's discus but i'm also just now feeding back

As discussed, please find attached the following corporate records prepared
for your review:

*1. Directors' Register*
*2. Officers' Register*
*3. Shareholders' Register* (I believe this is the same thing as a Members'
Register) why 'Members' Register'' - what is the statutory reference
I have doubled checked this, you are right I don't think there is members
register required for business corporations, I think it is only for not for
profit corporations that need to have it.

*4. Shareholders' Ledger*
With respect to the Shareholders' Ledger, which I understand to be the same
thing as a transfer register, there are a few things I wanted to note.

i'm not sure this is correct. i will double check but my practice has been
that each Shareholder has a ledger showing. I do see that that a combined
ledger has its advantages. What does the Act say?

s. 50 Securities records

   -

   50 (1) A corporation shall maintain a securities register in which it
   records the securities issued by it in registered form, showing with
   respect to each class or series of securities
   -

      (a) the names, alphabetically arranged, and the latest known address
      of each person who is or has been a security holder;
      -

      (b) the number of securities held by each security holder; and
      -

      (c) the date and particulars of the issue and transfer of each
      security.


I believe this would be the relevant provision but I am not 100% sure. But
it seems as though CBCA doesn't specify whether it is for each individual
SH or one combined one. Let me know what you think.

Firstly, the Director's Confirmation Resolutions document states there are
10,000,000 outstanding and issued shares, however, when I added up all of
the current shareholders' shares, the total was 9,674,000. Argh


I am wondering whether there were shares that were cancelled or why the
number is less than the 10,000,000.

i am also wondering.
  I think we need this information so the ledger can accurately reflect the
transactions that occurred.

absolutely agreed
 Additionally, I noted this directly in the document, but I believe the
first shares issued went to REIN Group of Companies Inc. and REIN
subsequently transferred shares to the rest of the shareholders. Finally,
we require some additional information to complete the ledger such as share
certificate numbers and consideration paid for shares.

i belive directors can also qualify as ISCs. the UBO of REIN Group of
Companies is Richard Dolan
Okay, thank you. I will update accordingly.


With this information, I think the ledger will give a clearer picture of
everything that occurred.

I also was not entirely sure whether each shareholder required an
individual ledger or if it was better to include all transactions in one
ledger, as I have done. Please let me know if you would like me to complete
one per shareholder, I am happy to do so.

The CBCA requires the following register, but I did not think it was
relevant in our case:

*1. Debt Obligations Register*

Is this correct. what is the exact CBCA provision?
I'm not entirely sure for this one I looked at the CBCA s. 50(1) but I
don't think it is the same as the debt obligations register and from this
website it says this but same as above I think it actually is for not-for
profit corporations.

https://ised-isde.canada.ca/site/corporations-canada/en/not-profit-corporations/corporate-records-and-filing-obligations
:


   1. if any debt obligations are issued by the corporation, a debt
   obligations register showing: the name and residential or business address
   of each debt obligation holder; an email address, if the debt obligation
   holder has consented to receiving information or documents electronically;
   the date on which each person named in the register became a debt
   obligation holder; the date on which each person named in the register
   ceased to be a debt obligation holder; and the principal amount of each of
   the outstanding debt obligations of each debt obligation holder



With respect to the individuals with significant control, and assuming that
the corporation has 10,000,000 issued and outstanding shares, to be an ISC
you would need to have 2,500,000 or more shares. Given that, the ISC would
only be applicable to REIN Group Companies Inc., but my understanding is
that you cannot list a corporation as an ISC; the individuals who control
REIN would have to be listed instead. As such, I think we need to know who
controls that corporation and by extension, who controls Legacy in order to
complete the ISC register. Let me know your thoughts on this.




*Matthew AJ* *Levine*

Barrister & Solicitor

emails.snippet: Hi Laura Let's discus but i'm also just now feeding back As discussed, please find attached the following corporate records prepared for your review: 1. Directors' Register 2. Officers'
emails.body:
Hi Laura

Let's discus but i'm also just now feeding back

As discussed, please find attached the following corporate records prepared
for your review:

*1. Directors' Register*
*2. Officers' Register*
*3. Shareholders' Register* (I believe this is the same thing as a Members'
Register) why 'Members' Register'' - what is the statutory reference
*4. Shareholders' Ledger*
With respect to the Shareholders' Ledger, which I understand to be the same
thing as a transfer register, there are a few things I wanted to note.

i'm not sure this is correct. i will double check but my practice has been
that each Shareholder has a ledger showing. I do see that that a combined
ledger has its advantages. What does the Act say?


Firstly, the Director's Confirmation Resolutions document states there are
10,000,000 outstanding and issued shares, however, when I added up all of
the current shareholders' shares, the total was 9,674,000. Argh


I am wondering whether there were shares that were cancelled or why the
number is less than the 10,000,000.

i am also wondering.
  I think we need this information so the ledger can accurately reflect the
transactions that occurred.

absolutely agreed
 Additionally, I noted this directly in the document, but I believe the
first shares issued went to REIN Group of Companies Inc. and REIN
subsequently transferred shares to the rest of the shareholders. Finally,
we require some additional information to complete the ledger such as share
certificate numbers and consideration paid for shares.

i belive directors can also qualify as ISCs. the UBO of REIN Group of
Companies is Richard Dolan

With this information, I think the ledger will give a clearer picture of
everything that occurred.

I also was not entirely sure whether each shareholder required an
individual ledger or if it was better to include all transactions in one
ledger, as I have done. Please let me know if you would like me to complete
one per shareholder, I am happy to do so.

The CBCA requires the following register, but I did not think it was
relevant in our case:

*1. Debt Obligations Register*

Is this correct. what is the exact CBCA provision?


With respect to the individuals with significant control, and assuming that
the corporation has 10,000,000 issued and outstanding shares, to be an ISC
you would need to have 2,500,000 or more shares. Given that, the ISC would
only be applicable to REIN Group Companies Inc., but my understanding is
that you cannot list a corporation as an ISC; the individuals who control
REIN would have to be listed instead. As such, I think we need to know who
controls that corporation and by extension, who controls Legacy in order to
complete the ISC register. Let me know your thoughts on this.




*Matthew AJ* *Levine*

Barrister & Solicitor


This message may contain confidential and / or privileged information and
is only to be used by the intended recipient. If you received this message
in error, please delete it and notify us. Thank you.

> accurately reflect the transactions that occurred.  Additionally, I noted

> to REIN Group of Companies Inc. and REIN subsequently transferred shares to
> the rest of the shareholders. Finally, we require some additional
> information to complete the ledger such as share certificate numbers and

Notes from “Appointment with Matthew Levine”

These notes have been sent to invited guests in your organization.

Open meeting notes

The content was auto-generated on February 25, 2026, 12:55 PM EST and may  
contain errors.


Summary


Ruo and Matthew Levine discussed the dissolution of Ruo's analytical  
testing lab, which closed due to an insurance incident and subsequent  
shareholder disagreements over how to proceed without sufficient funds to  
restart operations. A key focus of the conversation was the classification  
of operating funds that individual shareholders, including minority  
shareholder Ruo, contributed out of pocket after the initial investment,  
which Matthew Levine confirmed are generally treated as loans and are  
repaid first during winding-up before the remaining assets are divided  
according to shareholding. Ruo also raised concerns about potential  
self-dealing if a majority shareholder unilaterally funded the business as  
a loan, and they concluded by requesting Matthew Levine's fee structure for  
potential legal services related to the dissolution process.


Suggested next steps



Matthew Levine will send Ruo an email with a rough breakdown of the hourly  
rate and charge for a larger scope of services, and a sense of who they are.


Meeting records Document Notes by Gemini

Google LLC, 1600 Ampitheatre Parkway, Mountain View, CA 94043, USA

Matthew,

Your energy is your greatest asset.

It influences how you think, feel, and show up every day. But energy isn't just about physical stamina—it’s deeply tied to emotions, focus, and self-communication.

Think about a time when you felt unstoppable…

A time when ideas flowed easily, and you had the drive to take on anything. That state isn’t rare. It can be a daily experience.

💡 The Triad is your key to unlocking peak potential.

By using these three fundamental forces, you can create a powerful internal system that fuels you through any challenge. ⬇️

📝 The Triad: Your Blueprint for Peak Energy

Tony teaches that energy is both physical and emotional. Your feelings directly shape energy levels, and emotions are influenced by three interconnected forces.

🔥 Physiology: How you use your body

🎯 Focus: Where you direct your attention

🗣 Language: How you communicate with yourself

Mastering the forces of the Triad creates a powerful foundation that sustains momentum.

As a result, you’ll build a lasting framework for energy, clarity, and resilience.

⚓ Mastering Your Triad: The Energy Formula

💪 1. Physiology: Reset Your Body

Your physical state affects mental and emotional well-being.

Something as simple as a posture shift—standing tall, shoulders back, deep breathing—can create an energy boost.

Try these proven strategies to elevate your physiology daily. 👇

- Prioritize sleep: Reduce screen time before bed, dim the lights, and allow the body to rest deeply.

- Build strength: Tony’s trainer, Billy Beck, recommends squats, lunges, push-ups, and planks. Just 10 minutes daily strengthens the body and keeps you vibrant.

- Fuel wisely: Nutrient-dense foods (fruits, veggies, beans, lean proteins) may reduce disease risk. Swap one processed item for a whole food and notice the difference.

Small, consistent shifts in how you move, rest, and nourish your body create a foundation for lasting energy and vitality.

👀 2. Focus: Direct Your Attention

Where focus goes, energy flows.

Your attention determines your energy. Dwelling on problems drains you while focusing on possibilities fuels momentum.

- Morning reset: Start the day with Tony’s priming exercise (https://go.tonyrobbins.com/e3t/Ctc/OT+113/d4K3xc04/MXdWwmdFGdMW6P1CfR8txcD-W1m0cDV5KZFtbN2nfYxK3prCCW7lCdLW6lZ3lLW7KNC8X1cHSsQW8VPd0P5y1H2cW7vX6ZS8-NZzkW75q68D5P7gJLW8sg42858MpfvW4Dvx4h49ztzhW5fTrvK8H9t1DVHqSJV7cg7-8W8Wcnks6xMtXkW2sfv6y4-FbYPW83pmkw9f-0QHW1S4tXC5h7_7CW96rf713-m7hRW1_61cs7rFw08W1prdbk2z1ltLW5_dWGC75W-zxW2-gzM94WXymnW1KCMsg3cwcMyW1pldXt6RxwhYW2T5K8X1l4CLFW42YFTX25ywZgW6jTyHK1_TsGzW2vSt6P5pXM65W2-v4GW92YWLHf7F_ZRn04 ) —a mix of breathing, gratitude, and visualization that sets the tone for success.

- Intentional breaks: Short mental resets throughout the day improve clarity. Even two minutes of deep breathing can restore focus.

- Power questions: Replace "Why am I so tired?" with "How can I boost my energy in this moment?" The quality of your experience is a direct reflection of the questions you ask yourself.

By consciously directing your focus, you can shift your energy, enhance clarity, and create a more empowered state throughout the day.

💬 3. Language: Transform Your Communication

Words create reality, internally and externally.

Saying “I’m drained” reinforces fatigue. Saying “I’m recharging” encourages renewal.

- Notice patterns: Catch phrases that drain energy ("I can't." "I'm overwhelmed." "This is impossible.") and shift them.

- Interrupt & replace: When negative language appears, move physically and swap it for an empowering alternative.

- Elevate your self-talk: Speak to yourself as you would a close friend. Use encouraging, solution-focused language to reinforce confidence and energy.

The words you choose shape your emotions and energy. By shifting your language to be more empowering, you can create a more resilient and energized state.

💥 Your Challenge This Week: Create Your Triad Practice

📩 Take these three steps to create momentum:

- Physiology: Choose one habit to reinforce—better posture, deep breathing, hydration, or movement.

- Focus: Prioritize mental resets during the day, redirecting attention to something energizing.

- Language: Replace three energy-draining phrases with empowering alternatives.

These small shifts strengthen your energy system, allowing you to move toward your most important goals.

When you align your Triad—physiology, focus, and language—every aspect of well-being expands, fueling your energy, relationships, and fulfillment.

emails.body:
FINTRAC publishes a video on beneficial ownership requirements
-----------------------------------------------------------------

The Financial Transactions and Reports Analysis Centre of Canada (FINTRAC) has published a video that provides an overview of key beneficial ownership requirements under the _Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act_ (the Act) and associated Regulations.

This video is relevant for all businesses subject to the Act, except for title insurers.

Consult: Beneficial ownership: Understanding your requirements: https://fintrac-canafe.canada.ca/training-formation/web/beneficial-beneficiaire-eng

This video covers:

• Beneficial ownership requirements
• Beneficial Ownership Discrepancy Report
• Record-keeping requirements

Since October 1, 2025, businesses subject to the Act, except for title insurers, are required to submit a Beneficial Ownership Discrepancy Report to Corporations Canada when there is a material discrepancy between the beneficial ownership information they obtained and the information available in the Corporations Canada’s database about individuals with significant control.

For questions, please contact FINTRAC by telephone at 1-866-346-8722 (toll-free) or by email at guidelines-lignesdirectrices@fintrac-canafe.gc.ca.

To unsubscribe from the list, send a message to List-liste@fintrac-canafe.gc.ca: mailto:List-liste@fintrac-canafe.gc.ca?subject=Unsubscribe with “Unsubscribe” in the subject line.

FINTRAC is an independent federal government agency, operating at arm’s length from police, law enforcement and national security agencies. Its mandate is to receive, analyze, assess and, where appropriate, disclose information to assist in the detection, prevention and deterrence of money laundering, terrorist activity financing, sanctions evasion and threats to the security of Canada.

Financial Transactions and Reports Analysis Centre of Canada
24th floor, 234 Laurier Avenue West, Ottawa, Canada K1P 1H7
Government of Canada

Follow us on
X: @FINTRAC_Canada: https://x.com/FINTRAC_Canada
LinkedIn: FINTRAC Canada|CANAFE Canada: https://www.linkedin.com/company/18406872/
YouTube: FINTRAC Canada: https://youtube.com/@fintrac_canada

=================================================================


CANAFE publie une vidéo sur les exigences relatives aux bénéficiaires effectifs
-----------------------------------------------------------------

Le Centre d’analyse des opérations et déclarations financières du Canada (CANAFE) a publié une vidéo qui offre un aperçu des exigences clés relatives aux bénéficiaires effectifs figurant dans la _Loi sur le recyclage des produits de la criminalité et le financement des activités terroristes_ (la Loi) et les règlements connexes.

La vidéo est destinée à toutes les entreprises assujetties à la Loi, à l’exception des assureurs de titres.

Consultez le lien suivant : Bénéficiaires effectifs – Comprendre vos exigences: https://fintrac-canafe.canada.ca/training-formation/web/beneficial-beneficiaire-fra

La vidéo traite de ce qui suit :

• Les exigences relatives aux bénéficiaires effectifs
• La déclaration des écarts dans les renseignements sur la propriété effective
• Les exigences en matière de tenue de documents

Depuis le 1er octobre 2025, les entreprises assujetties à la Loi, à l’exception des assureurs de titres, doivent transmettre une déclaration des écarts dans les renseignements sur la propriété effective à Corporations Canada lorsqu’il y a des écarts significatifs entre l’information sur les bénéficiaires effectifs qu’ils ont obtenue et celle disponible dans les bases de données de Corporations Canada au sujet des personnes ayant un contrôle important.

Pour toute question, veuillez communiquer avec CANAFE par téléphone au 1-866-346-8722 (sans frais) ou par courriel à l’adresse guidelines-lignesdirectrices@fintrac-canafe.gc.ca.

Pour retirer votre nom de la liste, veuillez transmettre un message à List-liste@fintrac-canafe.gc.ca: mailto:List-liste@fintrac-canafe.gc.ca?subject=D%C3%A9sabonnement en indiquant « Désabonnement » comme objet du message.

CANAFE est un organisme fédéral autonome qui mène ses activités indépendamment des services de police et des organismes d’application de la loi et de sécurité nationale. Son mandat est de recevoir, d’analyser, d’évaluer et, le cas échéant, de communiquer des renseignements pouvant être utiles à la détection, à la prévention et à la dissuasion du blanchiment d’argent, du financement des activités terroristes, du contournement des sanctions et des menaces envers la sécurité du Canada.

Centre d’analyse des opérations et déclarations financières du Canada
234, avenue Laurier Ouest, 24e étage, Ottawa, Canada K1P 1H7
Gouvernement du Canada

Suivez-nous sur
X : @CANAFE_Canada: https://x.com/canafe_canada
LinkedIn : CANAFE Canada|FINTRAC Canada: https://www.linkedin.com/company/18406872/
YouTube : CANAFE Canada: https://youtube.com/@canafe_canada

emails.snippet: Dear Matthew Levine, 73727S You are receiving this reminder because the Law Society's records indicate that you have not yet filed your Annual Report for the past calendar year. Annual reports must
emails.body:
Dear Matthew Levine, 73727S
 
You are receiving this reminder because the Law Society's records indicate that you have not yet filed your Annual Report for the past calendar year.
 
Annual reports must be filed through your LSO Connects account by March 31. It is important to file by March 31, as the administrative suspension process will start after that date.
 
You will not receive any further reminders once you have successfully submitted your Annual Report.
 
If you believe you have already filed your Annual Report, please go to your LSO Connects account before March 31 and select the Annual Report tile to ensure that your Annual Report has been submitted. Once you have successfully submitted your Annual Report, the “Status Reason” will change to “Submitted”. 
 
 
Matthew Levine, 73727S
 
Vous recevez le présent rappel, car selon les dossiers du Barreau, vous n'avez pas encore déposé votre déclaration annuelle relative à la dernière année civile.
La déclaration annuelle doit être déposée par l'intermédiaire de ConnexionBarreauON au plus tard le 31 mars. Il est important de la déposer d'ici cette date, car après cette date, la suspension administrative prendra effet.

Vous ne recevrez pas d'autres rappels une fois votre déclaration annuelle envoyée.

Si vous croyez avoir déjà soumis votre déclaration annuelle, svp. Accédez a ConnexionBarreauON avant le 31 mars et sélectez la tuile Déclaration annuelle pour vous rassurer que la déclaration a bien été soumise. Une fois que votre déclaration de a été soumise avec succés, vous verrez que « Raison du statut » aura changé en « envoyé ».
emails.subject: Reminder - Annual Report Must Be Filed By March 31 / Rappel - La déclaration annuelle doit être déposée au plus tard le 31 mars

A new comment on the post "Barber Style: Top Tips for Short Hair" is waiting for your approval
https://barberismo.com/barber-style-top-tips-for-short-hair/

Author: Williambuh (IP address: 223.113.134.118, 223.113.134.118)
Email: ut.ici.s.i.s.ok.ib.2.2@gmail.com
URL: 
Comment: 
Лечение в наркологической клинике в Чехове удобно не только близостью к дому. Главный плюс — комплексный подход. Зависимость практически никогда не ограничивается только алкоголем или наркотиком: страдают сердце и сосуды, печень, нервная система, психика, отношения в семье и на работе. Если пытаться лечить только одно звено, например, периодически «чистить кровь» капельницами, без проработки причин и последствий, ситуация быстро возвращается к исходной точке. В клинике выстраивается последовательная работа: сначала стабилизируют организм, затем укрепляют психику, а дальше помогают менять привычный образ жизни, чтобы трезвость стала не кратким эпизодом, а новой нормой. 
Подробнее тут - http://narkologicheskaya-klinika-chekhov11.ru/

*From:* Matthew Levine <matthew@levinelegal.ca>
*Sent:* Monday, January 12, 2026 12:06 PM
*To:* Max Hill <mhill@mascore.ca>
*Subject:* Re: New Project



Hi Max



the patent lawyers who I know best are litigators but I do know some people
who do product development and will reach out.



I believe there may be government money available - have you looked into
that at all?



I see the next steps as:

   - *1. Legal Scoping*: counsel reviews the existing (U.S.) patent and
   scopes a design mandate focused on avoiding infringement under Canadian
   law. The scope and cost of this work will depend whether the goal is:


   - (a) to avoid infringing the existing patent (i.e., design-around), or
      - (b) to create something patentable by Mascore itself (i.e.,
      inventive and novel under the *Patent Act*).


   - *2 – Technical Development*: The product designer works within
   specified parameters to generate technical outputs, i.e. designs, models,
   and prototypes to achieve (a) or (b)
   - *3 – Legal Review*: counsel reviews the technical outputs and provides
   a follow-up opinion or informal assessment confirming whether the resulting
   design achieves (a) or (b)
   - *4 – Filing & Prosecution (if pursuing a patent strategy)*: If the
   objective under Step 1 includes creating patentable subject matter, a
   separate workstream is initiated for preparation and prosecution of
   Mascore’s own patent application.

what do you think of the above?











*Matthew AJ* *Levine*

Barrister & Solicitor

On Fri, Jan 9, 2026 at 12:30 PM Max Hill <mhill@mascore.ca> wrote:

There is a US company that owns a patent on a unique deep foundation
product.



It is technically a helical pile, but it is modified and has a continuous
flight added to it that pull down concrete during installation making the
foundation much stronger. Attached is the brochure for reference.



Also attached is the Canadian and US patent.



My thoughts are:



   - The patent drawing is technically different from what they actually
   produce, although similar. The patent shows a helical shape plate with 2-3
   revolution where what they actually build is a single revolution helix
   plate.
   - We build a similar product already without a helix plate. See attached
   drawing.
   - Need to figure out a way to prove this isn’t “novel”
   - What type of modification can we make to it to make our own novelty?
   - An American company produces this and has plans to bring it to Canada.
   We’d like to stop this by competing with it.



I understand you earn a patent lawyer, but do you have any contacts?



Please let us know your thoughts.



Max Hill, C.E.T

Mascore Helical Piles

905-807-4389



*From:* Matthew Levine <matthew@levinelegal.ca>
*Sent:* Friday, January 9, 2026 11:11 AM
*To:* Max Hill <mhill@mascore.ca>
*Subject:* Re: New Project



Hi Max



very interested. please send more info.



(i'm not a patent lawyer, as you know.)



happy new year





*Matthew AJ* *Levine*

Barrister & Solicitor

On Thu, Jan 8, 2026 at 9:12 AM Max Hill <mhill@mascore.ca> wrote:

HI Matthew,



Hope you are well.



I have a new project I am working on that involved patent expertise.



There is an existing product in our market that we would like to start
offering that is patented.



We would like to build a similar product without infringing or having
ourselves covered in the event of a legal action.



Is this something you can help us with?



If so, I will provide further details.



Max Hill, C.E.T

Mascore Helical Piles

emails.body:
Hi Gerard

Thanks for connecting with us. 

As it happens, my own family has a small relationship with Canadian art. My 
grandfather was a photographer. There is something about your paintings 
that I really enjoy. I also appears, without being an expert, that you have 
quite a comprehensive portfolio of Toronto-paintings. I always find this 
interesting, as the visual representation of Toronto is rather limited. 

In terms of the current situation with the condo board,  


*Matthew AJ* *Levine*

Barrister & Solicitor


1235 Bay Street, Suite 700, TORONTO, M5R 3K4

emails.snippet: Hi Max How are you? Specific responses are below. Would it be better to re-draft Section 8(e) to be a Contractual Property Payout instead of a support payment, and can we put a dollar-value cap on the
emails.body:
Hi Max

How are you?

Specific responses are below.

Would it be better to re-draft Section 8(e) to be a Contractual Property
Payout instead of a support payment, and can we put a dollar-value cap on
the 1.5% dividend to make it more predictable for a court? And set a base
amount of support (floor) and a “bonus” if the business does well? Have the
floor tied to my personal T1 and the ceiling tied to Mascore’s performance?




on "re-draft Section 8(e) to be a Contractual Property Payout instead of a
support payment" -- its a fascinating idea; but, I believe it solves the
wrong problem. Put differently, it does not solve the core problem of how
to manage support obligations. I would prefer to leave as is for this draft.



Max shall pay monthly spousal support equal to X% of his Line 15000 income
(the Base Support). In years where Mascore's net distributable income
exceeds $X, Max shall pay an additional 'Performance Bonus' equal to 1.5%
of such excess, provided that the total annual support (Base + Bonus) shall
never exceed a hard cap of $(Total Cap Amount).


how about 'Supplementary Support Payment'. What are the numbers?

I think this framework is good.




Can we reconfirm that the 1.5% is support and not equity and add a clause
stating that the 1.5% payment is a "personal covenant" by Max and does not
create any security interest, lien, or charge against the assets of Mascore.


yes.


let me know, and I will revise the document.




*Matthew AJ* *Levine*

Barrister & Solicitor

> I have a draft. I think it would be good for you to review and then we can
> consider next steps.
>

>
> The most relevant provisions are 8 and 10. Especially 8(b) and 8(e). 8(b)
> sets out the baseline support of the 1.5% "dividend". 8(e) sets out the
> right to the house if you walk away from the relationship. The challenge is
> that 8(e) is about property but the terms that you are seeking to achieve
> uses the property as support.
>
> In Ontario family law, property and support are seen as two distinct silos.
>
> Property is governed primarily by the* Family Law Act* (Part I) and
> equity, and is generally less difficult to contract out of.
>
> Support is governed primarily  by the* Divorce Act *and the *Family Law
> Act. *It is more difficult to contract out of support, which is what is
> being attempted with the potential transfer of the property. This deal is
> always going to be subject to residual judicial supervision.
>
> The terms we started off with used property as a substitute for support,
> and in doing so collapsed a distinction that courts take seriously.

>
>    - Property used as satisfaction of support via the “Enhanced
>    Settlement Amount"
>    - Support indexed to corporate economics because the agreement ties
>    periodic spousal support to Mascore’s distributable income.

emails.snippet: Hi Matthew, Thank you for sharing. Well it's a learning curve for me. I have read both agreements. So Stream Money cannot onboard, Equals can and SM is purely acting as an introducer to EM.
emails.body:
Hi Matthew,

Thank you for sharing. Well it's a learning curve for me. I have read both
agreements.
So Stream Money cannot onboard, Equals can and SM is purely acting as an
introducer to EM. Initially I thought we didn't need an EPA after finishing
the document read (this is my first time so I did some digging). In my
view, the EM client agreement should govern every element. However from a
legal/ commercial perspective it seems that even if Equal Money onboards SM
clients, the SM client is still considered to be interacting with Stream
Money commercially. I see two different aspects used here: a) from a
regulatory lens, and b) from a legal/commercial lens. Keen to understand:
if something goes wrong with the onboarding or funds who is liable?
I think a client-facing agreement may be required considering that SM is
branding the service, commercially involved , invoicing clients directly,
providing the front-end tech platform, and intends to have contractual
control over the introduced clients. It is important to understand that
even if Equals is the regulated entity, clients might perceive they are
using Stream's platform as a Stream client. Please correct me if I
misunderstood.

I'll be in the office tomorrow. Let's pick up.

Thanks and regards
*Tulika Dhar *
Head of Compliance

emails.body:
Hi Matthew

I will get my accountant to calculate my Mom's capital gains tax , they
already have done work on her income tax, and their familiar with her file.
    Concerning the Probate, or ( Estate Administration Tax).,I will not
apply,or pursue,for any kind of refund, not worth it , plus the headache
and cost of it ,as you mentioned ,no thanks..It's been paid, that's the
important thing.
    Yes,that would be great if your bookkeeper ,as you mentioned, can send
the total cost of the legal fees or the trust ledger ofcourse,as soon as
available or possible.
     This way we can start working on,  calculating the capital gains tax
owing right away.

Thanks

Zeljko

On Fri., Feb. 20, 2026, 3:50 p.m. Matthew Levine <matthew@levinelegal.ca>
wrote:

> Hi Zeljko
>
> Thanks and sorry for silence. its been unusually busy.
>
> I do not know 100% that I can calculate what is owed on the capital gains
> and I would normally suggesting reaching out to your accountant.
>
> In terms of the potential revaluation of the Estate Administration Tax. My
> understanding is that if new information about the Fair Market Value at the
> time of passing comes to light, then a revised Estate Information Return
> should be submitted to the Ministry of Finance. But, it is not guaranteed
> that the Ministry will reassess the tax payable. The Ministry will focus on
> whether there is new information that results in the FMV having been
> incorrectly calculated. Simply the fact that the shares were sold for less
> than the original FMV is not sufficient.   There may technically be a
> refund available, but the cost of proving the historical value needs to be
> taken into account. I believe it would most likely exceed the recovery. I
> will ask a colleague for a second opinion. let me know what you think.
>
> I will get my bookeeper to prepare and send over the trust ledger. I hope
> you have a good weekend and sorry not to be able to provide a more
> immediate positive response.
>
> *Matthew AJ* *Levine*
>

emails.snippet: Hi Matthew, I really don't think this lead qualifies. Note: - Spoke with Gerard Caraghamian, solo artist in the art publishing business. - Gerard explained that the condo board president verbally
emails.body:
Hi Matthew,

I really don't think this lead qualifies.

Note:
- Spoke with Gerard Caraghamian, solo artist in the art publishing business.
- Gerard explained that the condo board president verbally asked him to
create a design for the building’s 50th anniversary. He completed the work
(including photography and framing), but the board rejected it and did not
provide compensation.
- No written agreement or solid witnesses; only his wife was present but
cannot confirm the arrangement.
- Gerard is seeking legal guidance to determine if he has a case. He
prefers to work on a contingency basis (no upfront payment).
- I will review the matter with Matthew Levine and follow up with Gerard
via email regarding next steps.
- Gerard offered a limited edition print as a gesture, even if no legal
action proceeds.

Thanks!
Grace

---------- Forwarded message ---------
From: gerardparaghamian gerardparaghamian <gerardparaghamian@sympatico.ca>
Date: Tue, Feb 24, 2026 at 6:03 AM
Subject: Re: Thank You for Reaching Out to Levine Law
To: Grace Mendoza <grace@levine-law.ca>


Hello Grace,



I am a well known artist in Canada, (Official Artist of the SkyDome) etc.

I was verbally asked by my condo board of director president to do a design
for the

building's 50th. Anniversary. I obliged and did a beautiful finished design
that

everyone liked, then to my horror the board said that they did not like
what I did,

and that was that. I asked for $1.000 and I never heard from them again. A
project

like this would have been easily thousands more.

Do I have any legal recourse even though there is nothing written or signed.



Please advise.



Sincerely.



Gerard Paraghamian / 416-417-5956        www.theartofgerardparaghamian.com

                                                              Click on
"MyBooks" to view my 2 big art books.

                                                              Click on
"News" to read articles





------ Original Message ------
From: grace@levine-law.ca
To: gerardparaghamian@sympatico.ca
Sent: Monday, February 23rd 2026, 15:58
Subject: Thank You for Reaching Out to Levine Law


Hi Gerard,

Thank you for submitting your form. I see that you prefer to be contacted
by email, so I’m reaching out here to connect.

We’d be glad to learn more about your matter and how Levine Law can assist
you. When you have a moment, could you please share a few additional
details about your situation and the type of support you’re looking for?

Once we have a better understanding, we can advise on next steps and, if
appropriate, arrange a consultation.

I look forward to your reply.

Best regards,



*Grace Mendoza*

Client Intake Coordinator





*Levine Law*

1235 Bay Street, Suite 700, TORONTO, M5R 3K4

T: +1 (647) 598-2598

| Prospective client is a well-known artist based in Canada.

Hi Matthew,

Trust accounting violations are one of the fastest ways for a law firm to face serious consequences, and most issues aren’t intentional. They stem from misunderstood rules, incomplete reconciliations, or relying on the wrong tools.

Join us on February 26th at 12pm CST for a live CLE webinar, Trust accounting done right: A step-by-step guide to 3-way reconciliation for law firms, presented by Kelley Brubaker, CPA. We’ll break down trust accounting requirements and walk through how to perform a proper three-way reconciliation.

Key takeaways include:

- Identifying common errors that trigger bar scrutiny
- Understanding ethical obligations tied to handling client funds
- Applying best practices for documentation, reconciliation cadence, and audit readiness

And if you can’t make it, no problem! The on-demand version will be available on [our webinar resource](https://www.8am.com/webinars/?utm_source=webinar&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=8am-evergreen-trustaccountingclewebinarinviteemail) page on February 27th.

With your success in mind,

8am™

emails.snippet: Dear Village Shul Community, As we reflect on the success of last week's campaign we are filled with immense gratitude and pride. Together, we set out to raise 360000, and together, we raised over
emails.body:
Dear Village Shul Community,

As we reflect on the success of last week's campaign we are filled with immense gratitude and pride.

Together, we set out to raise $360,000, and together, we raised over $520,000. This achievement is not only about the funds raised, but about what it represents: a united community that believes deeply in our mission and in one another.

Your generosity sends a powerful message of commitment, strength, and love for our shul and everything it stands for. Because of you, we are able to continue growing, inspiring, and strengthening Jewish life for so many individuals and families.

On behalf of the Board of Directors, our administrators, and our dedicated staff team, thank you for your trust, your partnership, and your unwavering support.

Wishing you and your families a wonderful week filled with blessings.

With deep appreciation,
Rabbi Sytner, Rabbi Katz, The Board of Directors,
Shul Administration, and Staff Team

           The Village Shul
1072 Eglinton Avenue West
Toronto, ON M6C 2E2
www.ourvillageshul.com
         
Unsubscribe | Manage Preferences

emails.snippet: A candid, practical session on succession planning for Canadian business owners. Across Canada, many small business owners are approaching an important crossroads. Whether retirement is a few years
emails.body:
Across Canada, many small business owners are approaching an important crossroads. Whether retirement is a few years away or simply on the horizon, questions about succession are becoming more pressing.

If you are thinking about stepping back, planning for succession, or exploring your options, you may be asking:
*
What is my business really worth?
*
Who could realistically take over?
*
How long does a transition take?
*
Where do I even begin?
The transition process can feel complex and emotional. That’s why Digital Main Street is pleased to share this practical and candid webinar designed specifically for business owners who want to better understand their options and begin planning their next chapter. The webinar is hosted by our Founder, John Kiru!

Bringing Clarity to Succession Planning
Date: March 3
Time: 9:00 AM EST
Location: Live on Zoom
Cost: Free

Registration: https://us06web.zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_NQrGZ5KYTIexPeGRZbnUug https://us06web.zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_NQrGZ5KYTIexPeGRZbnUug [ https://us06web.zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_NQrGZ5KYTIexPeGRZbnUug ]

During this session, you will learn:
*
Why succession often feels overwhelming
*
The most common barriers owners face
*
Different transition paths, including family transitions, employee share ownership plans, and third-party sales
*
The key stages of a sale, from business readiness and valuation to due diligence, financing, and transition
*
How thoughtful planning protects confidentiality and strengthens negotiating confidence
This webinar is ideal for business owners across Canada who are considering exiting their business within the next 10 years, or who simply want to understand their long-term options.

Speakers:
John Kiru, CEO, Toronto Association of Business Improvement Areas (TABIA) and Founder of Digital Main Street
Alison Anderson, Founder, SuccessionMatching

Confidentiality: Audience members will not see who else is attending.
Small businesses are the backbone of communities across Canada. Ensuring smooth transitions helps protect jobs, preserve local economies, and safeguard the legacy you have worked hard to build.

If you are beginning to think about your next step, even if it feels early, this session will provide clarity, structure, and practical insight.

https://us06web.zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_NQrGZ5KYTIexPeGRZbnUug Register Now

 

Digital Main Street Partners

https://digitalmainstreet.ca/

Comment: 
Кодирование от алкоголизма в Чехове для многих семей становится тем рубежом, после которого зависимость перестаёт казаться «временной слабостью» и начинает восприниматься как диагноз, с которым можно и нужно работать. До этого момента обычно проходят годы: чередуются запои и трезвые периоды, звучат обещания «больше такого не будет», меняются напитки, придумываются правила вроде «пью только по выходным» или «только пиво». Но рано или поздно семья замечает, что именно алкоголь диктует распорядок дня, влияет на настроение, разрушает здоровье и отношения. В этот момент становится очевидно: без сильного внешнего ограничителя и профессиональной помощи просто «взять себя в руки» уже не получается.

emails.body: A new comment on the post "Barber Style: Top Tips for Short Hair" is waiting for your approval https://barberismo.com/barber-style-top-tips-for-short-hair/ Author: MarioFoula (IP address: 45.67.230.75, vm15271406.example.com) Email: g.lov.e.rm.a.so.n.5.9@gmail.com URL: Comment: Кодирование от алкоголизма в Чехове для многих семей становится тем рубежом, после которого зависимость перестаёт казаться «временной слабостью» и начинает восприниматься как диагноз, с которым можно и нужно работать. До этого момента обычно проходят годы: чередуются запои и трезвые периоды, звучат обещания «больше такого не будет», меняются напитки, придумываются правила вроде «пью только по выходным» или «только пиво». Но рано или поздно семья замечает, что именно алкоголь диктует распорядок дня, влияет на настроение, разрушает здоровье и отношения. В этот момент становится очевидно: без сильного внешнего ограничителя и профессиональной помощи просто «взять себя в руки» уже не получается.
